Uhm, nit of a nit: I think `getValidatedExtensionDetails` seems to be expecting an already validated extension. Someone would use it like:

```js
if (isValidExtension(extensionName)) {
   const extension = getValidatedExtensionDetails(extensionName)
}
```

I think `validateExternalExtension` is a good name since we are not prefixing it with `is` (which it leads to think that the return value is a bool). 

If we really want to be explicit we could use something like `validateAndLoadExternalExtension`.

Open!!

PS. Having `{ repository: string; branch?: string; isTrusted: boolean } | string>` as return type bothers me more than the name of the function since it makes the _client use_ more complex.

No strong feelings either. 

I like `$$var$$` slightly better (even if it's not needed) because it delimits the variable a bit better and it's easier to parse for me

```ts
 mainnet: {
      url: `https://eth-mainnet.alchemyapi.io/v2/\${providerApiKey}`,
      accounts: ["$$$deployerPrivateKey"],
    },
    sepolia: {
      url: `https://eth-sepolia.g.alchemy.com/v2/\${providerApiKey}`,
      accounts: ["$$deployerPrivateKey$$"],
    },
```

But happy either way!

Regarding losing comments on deepMerge. I'm here with Shiv and Cursor and we came with a (hacky) solution if we wanted to use it.

Change utils `stringify` function to (compact = false + magic comment placement):
```js
export const stringify = (val, comments = {}) => {
  let str = inspect(val, { 
    depth: null, 
    compact: false,
    maxArrayLength: null, 
    maxStringLength: null
  });
  
  // Add comments above their respective properties
  if (Object.keys(comments).length > 0) {
    str = str.replace(/^\s*(\w+):/gm, (match, prop) => {
      const indent = match.match(/^\s*/)[0];
      return comments[prop] 
        ? `${indent}// ${comments[prop]}\n${match}`
        : match;
    });
  }

  return str
    .replace(/"\$\$([^"]+)\$\$"/g, '$1')
    .replace(/'\$\$([^']+)\$\$'/g, '$1')
    .replace(/(['"])(.*?\$\{.*?\}.*?)\1/g, '`$2`');
};

```

And you could use it in the template like:

```js
const scaffoldConfig = ${stringify(finalConfig, {
  targetNetworks: "The networks on which your DApp is live",
  pollingInterval: "The interval at which your front-end polls the RPC servers for new data",
  alchemyApiKey: "Your Alchemy API key for interacting with Ethereum networks",
  walletConnectProjectId: "Your WalletConnect project ID for connecting to mobile wallets",
  onlyLocalBurnerWallet: "Only show the Burner Wallet when running on hardhat network"
})} as const satisfies ScaffoldConfig;
```

(fake ai comments lol)

We could also made it multi-line adding (\n).

A bit hacky, but it would solve the issue if we wanted.
